Introduce the base view model
```
abstract class BaseActivityViewModel: ViewModel() {
 abstract fun listDocQueue()
}
```


Your base activity class could be generic and have a method to create a view model instance:
```
public abstract class BaseActivity&lt;ViewModelT: BaseActivityViewModel&gt;: Activity {
  protected open fun getViewModelFactory(): ViewModelProvider.Factory? = null

  protected val viewModel: ViewModelT by lazy {
      val viewModelFactory = getViewModelFactory()
      if(viewModelFactory != null) {
         ViewModelProvider(this, viewModelFactory).get(viewModelClass)
      } else {
         ViewModelProvider(this).get(viewModelClass)
      }
  }
}

```

Then define your ViewModels and Activities based on your needs

```
class ActivityViewModel1 : BaseActivityViewModel() {
   override fun listDocQueue() { ... }
}

class ActivityViewModel2 : BaseActivityViewModel() {
   override fun listDocQueue() { ... }
}
```

```
class Activity1: class BaseActivity&lt;ActivityViewModel1&gt;() {
   override onCreate(...) {
      onCreate(...)
      viewModel.listDocQueue()
}

class Activity2: class BaseActivity&lt;ActivityViewModel2&gt;() {
   override onCreate(...) {
      onCreate(...)
      viewModel.listDocQueue()
}
```

Also make sure you have provided ViewModelFactory in case you need that.

According to the latest architecture guidelines you should be passing usecases to the viewModel, instead of exposing repository and each Use-case handles a specific task. it makes testing and maintaining code very easy. I recommend you use some kind of dependency inject as-well I personally use Dagger-Hilt. it makes it very easy. 

Repository

    interface Repository {}

Repositoryimpl

    class RepositoryImpl @Inject constructor(
    private val Dao: Dao) : Repository {}

UseCase

    class getWordFromRep(
    private val repository: Repository) {
        suspend operator fun invoke(){
          repository.getWord()
       } 
    }

Than in ViewModel

    class HomeViewModel @Inject constructor(
         private val getWord: GetWordFromRep
       ) : ViewModel(){
         fun getWord() = getword()
    }

And for Di you will be making a module

    @Module
    @InstallIn(SingletonComponent::class)
    object AppModule {
    @Provides
    @Singleton
    fun provideGetWordFromRep(repository: RepositoryImpl) = GetWordFromRep(repository)
    }

I recommend you watch the use-case video by [Philipp Lackner][1] It really helped me understand it. 

Also I recommend using Flows and states instead of livedata it really makes getting data in views easier and makes the code much cleaner.


  [1]: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ufq3LJ-5P6s

